{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01C4BCGJh54tUdSBFVekTnrm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1‚Üí# Workflows\n     2‚Üí\n     3‚ÜíCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4‚Üí\n     5‚Üí## Workflow Locations\n     6‚Üí\n     7‚ÜíCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8‚Üí\n     9‚Üí**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ‚Äî Run inside a Docker\n    10‚Üícontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11‚Üístandard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12‚Üí\n    13‚Üí**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ‚Äî Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14‚Üíprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15‚Üídispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16‚Üípoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17‚Üí\n    18‚ÜíThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19‚Üífile is a parse error.\n    20‚Üí\n    21‚Üí## Concepts\n    22‚Üí\n    23‚Üí| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24‚Üí|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25‚Üí| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26‚Üí| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27‚Üí| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28‚Üí| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    29‚Üí| done     | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî successful completion                     |\n    30‚Üí| abort    | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî failure with error reporting              |\n    31‚Üí\n    32‚Üí## Step Types\n    33‚Üí\n    34‚ÜíStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35‚Üí\n    36‚Üí**agent** (has `prompt`) ‚Äî Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37‚Üíto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38‚Üícontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39‚Üí\n    40‚Üí**script** (has `run`) ‚Äî Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41‚Üíany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42‚Üí\n    43‚Üí**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ‚Äî Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44‚Üíuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45‚Üí\n    46‚ÜíA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47‚Üíparse error.\n    48‚Üí\n    49‚Üí## DSL Syntax\n    50‚Üí\n    51‚Üí```\n    52‚Üíworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53‚Üí  step code {\n    54‚Üí    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55‚Üí    container {\n    56‚Üí      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57‚Üí      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58‚Üí    }\n    59‚Üí    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60‚Üí  }\n    61‚Üí\n    62‚Üí  step check {\n    63‚Üí    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64‚Üí    results = [pass, fail]\n    65‚Üí  }\n    66‚Üí\n    67‚Üí  step review {\n    68‚Üí    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69‚Üí    input = step.code.output\n    70‚Üí    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71‚Üí  }\n    72‚Üí\n    73‚Üí  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step\n    74‚Üí  code:success -> check\n    75‚Üí  code:fail -> abort\n    76‚Üí  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77‚Üí\n    78‚Üí  check:pass -> review\n    79‚Üí  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80‚Üí\n    81‚Üí  review:approved -> done\n    82‚Üí  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83‚Üí}\n    84‚Üí```\n    85‚Üí\n    86‚Üí## Key Properties\n    87‚Üí\n    88‚Üí**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89‚Üífield makes it a script step.\n    90‚Üí\n    91‚Üí**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92‚Üíreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93‚Üí\n    94‚Üí**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95‚Üíexisting ones by rewiring ‚Äî without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96‚ÜíCloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97‚Üí\n    98‚Üí**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99‚Üíwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100‚Üí\n   101‚Üí## Host Workflow Example\n   102‚Üí\n   103‚Üí```\n   104‚Üí# .cloche/host.cloche ‚Äî runs on the host machine\n   105‚Üíworkflow \"main\" {\n   106‚Üí  step prepare-prompt {\n   107‚Üí    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   108‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   109‚Üí  }\n   110‚Üí\n   111‚Üí  step develop {\n   112‚Üí    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   113‚Üí    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   114‚Üí    results       = [success, fail]\n   115‚Üí  }\n   116‚Üí\n   117‚Üí  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   118‚Üí  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   119‚Üí  develop:success        -> done\n   120‚Üí  develop:fail           -> done\n   121‚Üí}\n   122‚Üí```\n   123‚Üí\n   124‚ÜíThe `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n   125‚Üí`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\n   126‚Üícompletes.\n   127‚Üí\n   128‚Üí## Execution Model\n   129‚Üí\n   130‚Üí**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   131‚Üícontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   132‚Üíwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   133‚ÜíAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   134‚Üí\n   135‚Üí**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   136‚Üísteps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\n   137‚Üístandard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\n   138‚Üíetc.) are injected into each step.\n   139‚Üí"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9be06376-5a43-40f9-8380-030cf073c859","uuid":"88550078-ea2d-443a-ad1e-cd6b853689d7","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ‚Äî Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ‚Äî Runs on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) ‚Äî Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) ‚Äî Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ‚Äî Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n  step code {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    container {\n      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    }\n    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n  }\n\n  step check {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [pass, fail]\n  }\n\n  step review {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    input = step.code.output\n    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step\n  code:success -> check\n  code:fail -> abort\n  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n\n  check:pass -> review\n  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n\n  review:approved -> done\n  review:changes_requested -> code\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring ‚Äî without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche ‚Äî runs on the host machine\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\ncompletes.\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\nsteps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\nstandard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\netc.) are injected into each step.\n","numLines":139,"startLine":1,"totalLines":139}}}
