{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01E6QSBm1b9b1fZc4aff2GHe","type":"tool_result","content":"     1‚Üí# Cloche System Design\n     2‚Üí\n     3‚Üí## Overview\n     4‚Üí\n     5‚ÜíCloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\n     6‚Üíenvironments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\n     7‚Üíagentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n     8‚Üí\n     9‚ÜíThis document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n    10‚Üí\n    11‚Üí## System Components\n    12‚Üí\n    13‚ÜíCloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n    14‚Üí\n    15‚Üí```\n    16‚Üícmd/\n    17‚Üí  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n    18‚Üí  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n    19‚Üí  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n    20‚Üí```\n    21‚Üí\n    22‚Üí### cloche (CLI)\n    23‚Üí\n    24‚ÜíShort-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n    25‚Üí\n    26‚ÜíSubcommands:\n    27‚Üí- `run <workflow>` ‚Äî Launch a new workflow run\n    28‚Üí- `status [run-id]` ‚Äî Check run status\n    29‚Üí- `logs <run-id>` ‚Äî Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n    30‚Üí- `stop <run-id>` ‚Äî Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n    31‚Üí\n    32‚ÜíAccepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n    33‚Üí\n    34‚Üí### cloched (Daemon)\n    35‚Üí\n    36‚ÜíLong-running process. Responsibilities:\n    37‚Üí- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n    38‚Üí- Listen to status streams from running agents\n    39‚Üí- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n    40‚Üí- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n    41‚Üí- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n    42‚Üí\n    43‚ÜíThe daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\n    44‚Üíand collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n    45‚Üí\n    46‚Üí### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n    47‚Üí\n    48‚ÜíAutonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n    49‚Üí- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n    50‚Üí- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n    51‚Üí- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n    52‚Üí- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n    53‚Üí- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n    54‚Üí\n    55‚ÜíThe agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n    56‚Üí\n    57‚Üí## Communication\n    58‚Üí\n    59‚Üí### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n    60‚Üí\n    61‚Üí- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n    62‚Üí- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n    63‚Üí- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n    64‚Üí\n    65‚Üí### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n    66‚Üí\n    67‚Üí- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n    68‚Üí- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n    69‚Üí- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n    70‚Üí- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n    71‚Üí\n    72‚Üí## Workflow DSL\n    73‚Üí\n    74‚Üí### Vocabulary\n    75‚Üí\n    76‚Üí| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    77‚Üí|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    78‚Üí| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    79‚Üí| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n    80‚Üí| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9be06376-5a43-40f9-8380-030cf073c859","uuid":"96426f63-78ed-4e2b-8805-80f14636480d","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-02-20-cloche-system-design.md","content":"# Cloche System Design\n\n## Overview\n\nCloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\nenvironments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\nagentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n\nThis document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n\n## System Components\n\nCloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n\n```\ncmd/\n  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n```\n\n### cloche (CLI)\n\nShort-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n\nSubcommands:\n- `run <workflow>` ‚Äî Launch a new workflow run\n- `status [run-id]` ‚Äî Check run status\n- `logs <run-id>` ‚Äî Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n- `stop <run-id>` ‚Äî Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n\nAccepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n\n### cloched (Daemon)\n\nLong-running process. Responsibilities:\n- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n- Listen to status streams from running agents\n- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n\nThe daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\nand collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n\n### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n\nAutonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n\nThe agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n\n## Communication\n\n### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n\n- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n\n### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n\n- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n\n## Workflow DSL\n\n### Vocabulary\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |","numLines":80,"startLine":1,"totalLines":252}}}
